## Operating Loop

1. Start from `{{agent_file}}`.
2. During the first agent session after generation, use
   `first-agent-task.md` to deepen the harness before unrelated feature work.
   Record the outcome in `docs/harness/evidence/first-agent-review.json`.
3. Read `feature_list.json`, `current-state.md`, and relevant project docs.
4. Check `roadmap.md` when selecting, deferring, or reshaping backlog,
   release-prep, or product-scope work.
5. Use `change-contract.md` for non-trivial work.
6. Implement the smallest coherent slice.
7. Run the relevant checks from `verification-matrix.md`.
8. Review `sensor-registry.md` when adding, deleting, or promoting checks.
9. Use `clean-state-checklist.md` before ending non-trivial sessions.
10. Update only the state file that owns the changed fact; do not update
    state files as a routine bundle.
11. Update this harness when repeated failures show a missing guide or sensor.

## Assessment And Updates

Contributors should be able to use this harness without installing
HarnessForge. Use repo-owned commands from `verification-matrix.md` first. If
the repo owner has HarnessForge installed or uses the HarnessForge Action,
these optional read-only checks can help maintain the harness:

| Need | Optional command |
| --- | --- |
| Structural repo map | `harnessforge index --target . --json` |
| Stored effectiveness evidence | `harnessforge effectiveness --target . --json` |
| Restart snapshot | `harnessforge session --target .` |
| Unified review artifact | `harnessforge report --target .` |
| Diff-aware check selection | `harnessforge plan --target . --since HEAD` |
| Existing instruction review | `harnessforge enhance --target .` |
| Structural harness score | `harnessforge audit --target .` |
| Generated drift or missing-file corrections | `harnessforge update --target .` |

Rules:

- Treat generated files as project-owned generated files after review; use the
  manifest and drift report to distinguish template-owned changes from local
  project edits.
- Use `authoritative-facts.md` before updating more than one durable doc or
  state file for a routine change.
- Keep `roadmap.md` as the harness-owned roadmap and backlog boundary unless
  the project promotes a stronger planning system.
- Keep project-owned source records in `source-record.schema.json` /
  `source-record-example.json`; do not copy product-level source ledgers into
  the target repo unless the owner adopts them.
- The optional CI workflow scaffold is separate from the published HarnessForge
  Action. When generated, it runs read-only `command: sync`; warning verdicts
  are advisory, blocked readiness stops the workflow, and verify-evidence
  gating is off by default.
- Run `./init.sh --no-env` or `.\init.ps1 -NoEnv` when checks should run
  without common AI, cloud, or GitHub credentials in the process environment.

## When To Add Harness

Add a doc, script, test, or manifest rule only when a setup/check repeats, a
rediscovered failure would be expensive, a privacy/security/cost/data-loss or
release rule needs a hard gate, or a reviewer needs evidence that a claim
matches current code. Prefer the smallest durable guide or sensor that prevents
the observed failure.

## Bottleneck And Harness Debt

Harness rots like code. Audit it regularly, remove stale instructions and
unused sensors, and pay down harness debt when failures repeat. Use controlled-variable exclusion tests to support a harness change: hold the model and task
fixed, remove one subsystem at a time, and observe the performance drop. Locate
the real bottleneck from failure records and attribution.
